default_output_path="""
Default output PATH.

The default output PATH that MAGE will use when encrypting and or decrypting
an archive; the standard and recommended prefix is "." which is used to indicate
the sibling directory / location of the selected file(s).
"""

default_extension="""
Default extension.

The default file extension MAGE will use; the default being ".mage". About any file
extension is supported, with the format of ".[anything after]".

Keep in mind, the .mage file extension will be used for shell context intergation, no
other extension will work.
"""

mute_sfx="""
Mute SFX.

Mute any and all sound effects from playing in MAGE.
"""

sfx_vol="""
SFX volume.

Adjust how loud sound effects play in MAGE.
"""

include_hidden="""
Include hidden files / directories.

When enabled, MAGE will also package any files with the Windows hidden attribute to an archive when encrypting;
otherwise if disabled hidden files will not be added to archives.
"""

copy_file_properties="""
Copy file metadata.

When enabled MAGE will apply / copy custom file / folder properties, this does not include any system-harmful properties.
This is also mostly intended for Windows.
"""

chunk_size="""
Chunk size.

Adjust the chunk size to be used by MAGE during encryption and decryption.
A larger chunk size uses more memory but can slightly improve performance.
"""

default_cipher="""
Default AEAD cipher.

AES-256-GCM (OpenSSL based) is highly optimized for x86 and x64 CPUs that support a technology
called AES-NI (Advanced Encryption Standard - New Instructions) which greatly accelerates the overall
computing speed of AES-256-GCM and making it significantly faster than XChaCha20-Poly1305.

XChaCha20-Poly1305 (NaCl based) is a generally well optimized algorithm for encryption which works
great on most CPUs / machines that don't support AES-NI; resulting in a much faster target speed than
AES-256-GCM if AES-NI is unavailable.

Overall both algorithms are equally secure, there is no definitive "better" choice; just depends on your preference
and personal restraints.
"""

default_argon2_time="""
Argon2id time cost.

Set the time cost (number of iterations) for Argon2id key derivation; higher values increase resistance
against bruteforce attacks but take more time to compute. A time cost of 4-8 is generally recommended.
"""

default_argon2_memory="""
Argon2id memory cost.

Set the memory cost for Argon2id key derivation, higher values increase security against ASIC / GPU
attacks but require more RAM to compute. The general recommended RAM cost is 96MBs - 128MBs.
"""

default_argon2_parallelism="""
Default Argon2id parallelism.

Set the number of threads for Argon2id key derivation. This determines the degree of parallelism
used during key derivation; this can prevent multi-cored GPU / ASIC attacks, and the overall recommended
amount is 2 - 4 cores
"""

default_compression_algo="""
Compression algorithm.

ZSTD is the default algorithm MAGE picks; this algorithm is a mix between high compression rations (almost
on par as LZMA2) while maintaing a non-insufferable speed / general compression time cost. For most use cases it
is recommended to use the "Good" prefix.

LZMA2 is the same technology that 7-zip uses to squeeze out every last byte for the cost of time. LZMA2 is slow, compute
intensive and relies on complex algorithms to; as said, reduce file sizes as much as possible.
"""

default_compression_preset="""
Compression preset.

For both ZSTD and LZMA2 there are four presets, "Store", "Fast", "Good" and "ULTRAKILL"; each algorithm has different levels depending
on their mode but for most use cases it is recommended to use ZSTD with the "Good" preset selected.
"""

use_raw_compression="""
Use raw compression levels.

When this option is enabled instead of relying on compression presets you can manually adjust them for each algorithm,
this option is only recommended if you are familiar with both of the libraries and know your personal preference.
"""

default_compression_raw="""
Raw compression level.

Each algorithm has a unique scale for the levels; ZSTD supports all the way from 0 (no compression / store) to 22
which is best for file sizes but most costly and takes the longest. While LZMA2 supports levels from 0 - 9, each level
will always be more intensive than ZSTD and it is recommended to pick LZMA2's levels with caution.
"""